I got tired of reading a lot of pseudo legal opinions about who owns
email, so I asked our corporate lawyer. Here's the exchange:

>There has been a bitter exchange on the net lately because of the
>following, which appeared at the end of a posting:
>
>"Private email sent to me becomes my property and may be divulged."
>
>or something similar.
>
>You wouldn't believe the number of "legal opinions" this has spawned.
>Now, I remember from 25 years ago that correspondence is legally the
>property of the RECIPIENT. Is that correct? I suppose that this hasn't
>really been tested in the new electronic age.
>-- jwh

Unless I am bound by an obligation of confidence, then if you send me
something I can publish or divulge.  The obligation can arise under several
circumstances, but if someone sends me email I normally can redistribute.


        -Chad


